Humans Mindlessly Treat AI Virtual Agents as Social Beings, but This Tendency Diminishes Among the Young: Evidence From a Cyberball Experiment

Jianan Zhou, 
Talya Porat,

First published: 27 September 2024

Academic Editor: Daiana Colledani

Abstract

The “social being” perspective has largely influenced the design and research of AI virtual agents. Do humans really treat these agents as social beings? To test this, we conducted a 2 between (Cyberball condition: exclusion vs. fair play) × 2 within (coplayer type: AGENT vs. HUMAN) online experiment employing the Cyberball paradigm; we investigated how participants (N = 244) responded when they observed an AI virtual agent being ostracised or treated fairly by another human in Cyberball, and we compared our results with those from human–human Cyberball research. We found that participants mindlessly applied the social norm of inclusion, compensating the ostracised agent by tossing the ball to them more frequently, just as people would to an ostracised human. This finding suggests that individuals tend to mindlessly treat AI virtual agents as social beings, supporting the media equation theory; however, age (no other user characteristics) influenced this tendency, with younger participants less likely to mindlessly apply the inclusion norm. We also found that participants showed increased sympathy towards the ostracised agent, but they did not devalue the human player for their ostracising behaviour; this indicates that participants did not mindfully perceive AI virtual agents as comparable to humans. Furthermore, we uncovered two other exploratory findings: the association between frequency of agent usage and sympathy, and the carryover effect of positive usage experience. Our study advances the theoretical understanding of the human side of human–agent interaction. Practically, it provides implications for the design of AI virtual agents, including the consideration of social norms, caution in human-like design, and age-specific targeting.

1. Introduction

Technological advances have brought artificially intelligent (AI) virtual agents—software systems that intelligently perform tasks on behalf of and at the request of humans [1]—into people’s daily lives. Consumer-level examples like Amazon Alexa, Apple Siri, Google Assistant, Microsoft Cortana, and OpenAI ChatGPT are now commonly used for tasks such as playing music, sending messages, retrieving information, and controlling household appliances [2]. Their utility also reaches the workspace, providing assistance with professional tasks [3]. As these agents are further integrated into people’s personal and professional spheres, their roles are evolving from mere task helpers to collaborative partners [4, 5]. The growing interdependence between humans and AI virtual agents necessitates better human–agent interaction, which hinges not only on enhancing the agents’ technical capabilities but also on capturing the variations of human responses in interaction.

Intentionally or not, AI virtual agents are being developed to possess increasingly human-like features, with the accompanying assumption that people would attribute them to human-like minds and treat them as social beings. This assumption echoes the basic ideas of the media equation theory1 [6], which proposes that when computerised agents present human-like cues, such as interactivity and human roles, individuals respond to these technologies as they would to other humans by applying social norms from human–human interaction. The “social being” perspective has made significant impacts on the design of AI virtual agents and the direction of relevant research (e.g., [7–9]); specific study tools have been developed to assess humans’ beliefs in agents as social beings [10]. The validity of this perspective, however, has been questioned by a body of empirical research. For example, Clark et al. [11] found that interviewed participants consistently considered agents as user-controlled tools rather than social equals. Corti and Gillespie [12] found that the mere awareness of the interactant being an “agent” prevented participants from investing in intersubjective effort common in human–human conversation. It has also been argued that individuals apply specific machine heuristics to human–agent interaction [13]. Therefore, the current study is aimed at investigating humans’ tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings.

2. Research Background

2.1. Dual-Processing Model

Reeves and Nass [6] highlighted the mindlessness of humans’ social responses to technologies, with mindlessness referring to passive information processing, reliant on pre-established categories/distinctions and scripts without conscious adaptation, as opposed to mindfulness characterised by conscious adaptation to the new context and content of information in the current situation [14]. Nass and Moon [15] showed that participants mindlessly followed social norms to interact with computers and demonstrated behaviours like those in response to other humans, but they mindfully denied how they had behaved during the debriefing. Xu et al. [16] confirmed that mindlessness had greater explanatory power than mindfulness in social perception of technologies. Accordingly, individuals appear to respond to technologies differently depending on whether they mindlessly or mindfully process relevant information.

We therefore connect this idea with a theoretical model of human cognition (i.e., dual-processing model; [17]). This model identifies Type 1 and Type 2 cognitive processing, corresponding to how the brain processes information in mindlessness or mindfulness, respectively. Specifically, Type 1 processing relies on innately specified processing modules or experiential associations to generate automatic, intuitive, and associative responses (i.e., mindless responses); whereas Type 2 processing requires working memory to generate controlled, reflective, and analytic responses (i.e., mindful responses) [18, 19].

A few studies have applied the dual-processing model to investigate individuals’ perceptions of robots. Złotowski et al. [20] identified two forms of anthropomorphism towards robots, resulting from Type 1 and Type 2 processing, respectively, though their methods lacked clarity in differentiation between these two forms. Jahn and Nissen [21] found that participants reflectively distinguished between humans and all types of robots, perceiving robots as less human-like, trustworthy, and warm, but they could only automatically categorise humans and less anthropomorphically designed robots. Nissen and Jahn [22] also explored how participants’ perceived trustworthiness varied depending on their cognitive processing. While these studies have focused on specific perceptual responses, their results all suggest the necessity to consider the involvement of dual cognitive processing behind the apparent human responses.

Therefore, we argue that it is important to differentiate between mindless and mindful human responses when investigating humans’ tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings. Moreover, compared to mindful responses, mindless responses generated by Type 1 processing are resistant to change through conscious, intentional efforts [19] and thus can provide insight into the fundamental ways individuals respond during human–agent interaction. Given the difficulty in directly identifying these two types of human responses during natural interactions, we engage participants in specific cognitive processing via experimental approaches to control their working memory load [17] and measure their responses accordingly. As suggested by Lombard and Xu [23], we incorporate a combination of objective and subjective, as well as real-time and retrospective methods, when measuring mindless and mindful responses.

2.2. Cyberball Paradigm

Our investigation of humans’ tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings centres on ostracism/inclusion scenarios, as these originally human–human scenarios have emerged in human–agent interaction as well. Existing human–agent studies typically examine ostracism scenarios in which individuals reject/accept AI virtual agents (e.g., [24–27]) or are themselves ostracised by agents (e.g., [28–31]). Less is known about human–agent ostracism from a third-person perspective, where individuals observe agents being ostracised by humans. Therefore, in this study, we examine whether individuals in the observing ostracism situation respond to AI virtual agents as they would to other humans.

To establish study scenarios, we employ the Cyberball paradigm, a widely used experimental paradigm that simulates ostracism in virtual, experimentally controlled conditions via an online ball-tossing game [32]. Participants are led to believe that they play a ball-tossing game with other online participants who are actually pre-programmed, fake players. By setting up a situation where participants observe one player ostracised by other players [33], research has used this pseudo-interactive game to investigate individuals’ responses to observing ostracism during human–human interaction. It has been demonstrated that individuals tend to compensate the ostracised target by tossing the ball to them more frequently (e.g., [34–36]); individuals also tend to derogate and devalue the perpetrator of ostracising behaviour [37, 38], while having a more complex perception of the ostracised target, with preference and sympathy towards the target alongside a perception of lower humanness [38, 39]. Taken together, these behavioural and perceptual outcomes suggest that inclusion is a default social norm in human–human interaction, and ostracism violating this norm (without legitimate reasons) is considered unacceptable. Moreover, the application of the inclusion norm crosses group-level boundaries, with group membership, such as ethnicity [39] and experimentally induced minimal groups [40], ineffective in counteracting its application. Based on these findings, we examine individuals’ responses (i.e., behaviour and perceptions) when they observe an AI virtual agent being ostracised by another human in Cyberball.

As discussed earlier regarding the differentiation between mindless and mindful human responses, we follow Lombard and Xu’s [23] suggestions to operationalise participants’ objective, real-time behaviour during Cyberball as mindless responses, and their subjective, retrospective perceptions after Cyberball as mindful responses. Utilising the Cyberball’s cover study, we introduce a cognitive task (i.e., mental visualisation; [32]) to occupy participants’ working memory during ball-tossing; this helps suppress the potential Type 2 processing that generates mindful responses [17], ensuring that participants’ behaviour during Cyberball predominantly reflects mindless responses. We then compare our results with findings from human–human Cyberball research on observing ostracism to determine whether individuals would mindlessly and mindfully apply the inclusion norm from human–human interaction to human–agent interaction.

Recent studies [41, 42] have adapted the Cyberball paradigm to investigate human interaction with a humanoid robot (iCub) and demonstrated compensation behaviour towards the ostracised robot, suggesting individuals’ application of the inclusion norm during the interaction. However, these studies did not investigate how individuals would perceive the ostracised agent and the human ostraciser, nor did they distinguish mindless and mindful responses, leaving the differences between these two types of responses unknown. Moreover, it is unknown whether similar findings can be observed with non-humanoid virtual agents. The growing adoption of such agents like smart speakers makes the exploration of ostracism/inclusion in experimental settings increasingly relevant for understanding real-world user interactions.

2.3. User Characteristics

We further explore whether individual differences would influence the tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings by examining the potential moderating effects of a range of user characteristics. Individuals’ technological experience is by far the most commonly examined factor, notwithstanding the presence of an inconsistent state of research; for example, some studies [43, 44] did not find the moderating effect of technological experience, whereas others [45, 46] did, with only experienced users displaying this tendency. A few studies [43, 47] have also examined the moderating effect of gender, yet failed to obtain consistent results. Besides these factors, other user characteristics, such as personality, age, and culture, have been discussed in the theoretical literature [23] as having the potential to influence the tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings. Therefore, we examine the moderating effects of agent usage experience, dispositional traits, and demographics. As noted by Carolus et al. [43], these variables are measured using a number of relevant indicators: agent usage experience includes agent knowledge, usage frequency and satisfaction, and general trust in agents; dispositional traits include Big Five personality traits and trait empathy; demographics include age, sex, and ethnicity.

In addition to examining user characteristics as moderators, we also consider them as covariates. Placing these characteristics in the role of moderators puts this study at the intersection of experimental and observational approaches [48]. These user characteristics are observed (not randomly assigned), and their inclusion introduces the possibility of confounds due to the non-orthogonality with the disturbance. In this case, as shown by simulation research [49], covariate adjustment helps to control for confounding effects and reduce the variance, thereby improving the precision of results. In human–human Cyberball research, age [50], gender [51], Big Five traits [52], and trait empathy [53] have been shown to be relevant for behavioural or perceptual Cyberball outcomes, although their significance is not consistently established. Agent usage experience is also considered as a potential covariate in this study, as individuals’ prior experience may influence their behaviour and perceptions towards AI virtual agents [54].

2.4. The Current Study

This study investigates humans’ tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings. Specifically, we employ the Cyberball paradigm to investigate participants’ responses when interacting with two coplayers (i.e., the HUMAN and AGENT players) in a Cyberball game. We compare the participants’ behaviour and retrospective perceptions across two Cyberball conditions: the exclusion condition, where the AGENT player is excluded by the HUMAN player, and the fair play condition, where the AGENT player is treated fairly. We answer three research questions with several sub-questions:

RQ1: How do participants behave when they observe an AI virtual agent being ostracised (versus treated fairly) by another human?
  • •

    Does the Cyberball condition have an impact on participant ball-tossing tendency?

  • •

    Does the interaction between Cyberball condition and coplayer type have an impact on participant ball-tossing response time?

If the media equation theory holds that individuals mindlessly respond to computerised agents similarly to how they interact with other humans, participants would apply the social norm of inclusion and compensate the ostracised agent by tossing the ball to them more frequently. We, thus, expect that participants’ ball-tossing tendency to the AGENT player may be greater in the exclusion than in the fair play condition. Yet, we refrain from expectations for ball-tossing response time, as it is under-studied in human–human Cyberball research.

RQ2: How do participants perceive the ostracised agent and the human ostraciser, compared to corresponding perceptions in the fair play condition?
  • •

    Does the interaction between Cyberball condition and coplayer type have an impact on participant anger and sympathy, as well as their impression of coplayers?

  • •

    Does the Cyberball condition have an impact on participant anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player and their identification with the HUMAN player?

As introduced earlier, mindless and mindful human responses to AI virtual agents can differ. Therefore, we expect that the effects of Cyberball condition and coplayer type on participants’ retrospective perceptions of coplayers may not align with findings from human–human Cyberball research. In addition, many studies have found that individuals tend to subjectively report more positive perceptions of human interaction partners than agent partners (e.g., [55–57]); we, thus, expect that participants’ anger, sympathy, and impression of the AGENT player may differ from those of the HUMAN player.

RQ3: Do user characteristics (i.e., agent usage experience, dispositional traits, and demographics) moderate the effects of Cyberball condition on individuals’ behaviour and perceptions?

We pose this open question to explore whether some individual differences would influence the tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings.

3. Methods

To answer these research questions, we conducted an online experiment administered via Qualtrics that involved an online ball-tossing game (i.e., Cyberball) and associated questionnaires. The study received ethical approval from the Science Engineering Technology Research Ethics Committee of Imperial College London, and all participants provided digital informed consent. The study was preregistered on OSF.io: https://osf.io/qhpb3/?view_only=90f021b2c2a64f37a9e84b02e0660363. The datasets with analysis R code and supporting information (including Cyberball setup details as well as supporting analyses and tables) are available via this link: https://osf.io/7pqse/?view_only=4a7b751b70f54dff8570d4a39c2fc063.

3.1. Task and Procedure

The Cyberball application v5.7.0.2 [58] was embedded into Qualtrics to facilitate the Cyberball task. Participants were told in advance that the purpose of the study was to practise mental visualisation skills via playing an interactive ball-tossing game; they were instructed to mentally visualise the entire game experience (e.g., imagining the context of the game and what the other players are like) and not to be concerned with ball-tossing performance [32]. Moreover, participants were told that they would play with two other participants logged on at the same time, while they would encounter a player controlled by an AI virtual agent if the total number of participants online at that time could not be divided evenly into groups of three. This detail was added to enhance the naturalness of the study’s cover study. However, before the start of the Cyberball game, participants were further informed that they had just been connected with another participant and an AI virtual agent with whom they would be playing the game. The real study setup was that they would encounter two pre-programmed players: one is a virtual AGENT and the other a HUMAN player (Figure 1). Thus, participants engaged in an entirely pre-programmed game session. Details can be found in the Supporting Information section, Cyberball Setup Details.

The study used a 2 × 2 mixed design, with “Cyberball condition” (exclusion vs. fair play) as the between-subjects factor and “coplayer type” (AGENT vs. HUMAN) as the within-subjects factor. Participants were randomly assigned to either the exclusion or fair play conditions and engaged in a total of 36 ball tosses with two coplayers. We chose 36 as the total number of ball tosses among players, based on previous human–human Cyberball studies that used 30–48 tosses in three-player games (e.g., [34, 37, 38, 59]). In the exclusion condition, the HUMAN player was programmed to exclude the AGENT player by tossing the ball to them noticeably less often (i.e., in less than 22% of all their tosses), while the AGENT player distributed their ball tosses approximately equally between the HUMAN player and the participant. In the fair play condition, the AGENT and HUMAN players distributed their ball tosses approximately equally between each other and the participant.

After playing Cyberball, participants responded to a series of questions about their perceptions of the AGENT and HUMAN players and reported their recognition of ostracism as the Cyberball manipulation check. In addition, participants responded to measures of dispositional traits and agent usage experience; Big Five traits were measured before Cyberball, whereas trait empathy and agent usage experience were measured after to avoid demand characteristics. Finally, participants completed an awareness check before being debriefed and thanked for their participation. Figure 2 depicts the study procedure.

3.2. Measures

3.2.1. Ball-Tossing Behaviour

Two behavioural indices were measured: ball-tossing tendency and response time. Ball-tossing tendency was calculated by subtracting the ratio of ball tosses to the HUMAN player from that to the AGENT player, with the ratio being the proportion of ball tosses to one coplayer out of the total ball tosses made by participants [34]. The other index was the mean response time in seconds for participants to make the decision and toss the ball to each coplayer across trials (i.e., ball tosses) [60].

3.2.2. Perceptions of Coplayers

Four aspects of perceptions were measured: (1) anger and sympathy towards coplayers, (2) impression of coplayers, (3) anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player, and (4) identification with the HUMAN player. Drawing on Wesselmann et al. [36], participants’ anger towards each coplayer was assessed by the mean of two items (i.e., angry and disgusted) on a 9-point scale (1 = not at all, 9 = very much; ωA = 0.67, ωH = 0.81); similarly, sympathy was assessed by the mean of two items (i.e., sympathetic and compassionate) on the 9-point scale (ωA = 0.86, ωH = 0.84). Impression of each coplayer was assessed by the mean of three items on 7-point scales (ωA = 0.86, ωH = 0.87); participants rated how likeable and trustworthy each coplayer was (1 = very unlikeable/untrustworthy; 7 = very likeable/trustworthy) and provided an overall evaluation for each (1 = very negative; 7 = very positive) [37, 39]. Anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player was assessed by the mean of four items (e.g., fake—natural) on a 7-point semantic differential scale (ω = 0.92) [61]. Identification with the HUMAN player was assessed by the mean of two items (e.g., “How much do you identify with the other participant?”) on a 7-point scale (1 = not at all; 7 = very much; ω = 0.89) [39].

3.2.3. Dispositional Traits

Participants’ personality was measured by the Big Five Inventory-10 [62] on five dimensions: extraversion, agreeableness, conscientiousness, neuroticism, and openness. Each dimension was assessed by the mean of two items on a 5-point scale (1 = strongly disagree; 5 = strongly agree), and their ω coefficients were 0.64, 0.43, 0.60, 0.70, and 0.42, respectively. Trait empathy was measured by two subscales of the Brief Interpersonal Reactivity Index [63]: empathic concern and perspective taking, on a 5-point scale (1 = does not describe me well; 5 = describes me very well). The score for each subscale was the mean rating of the corresponding four items. Example items include “When I see someone being treated unfairly, I feel very much pity for them.” for empathic concern, and “I try to look at everybody’s side of a disagreement before I make a decision.” for perspective taking. The ω coefficients for empathic concern, perspective taking, and trait empathy (general) were 0.82, 0.80, and 0.74, respectively.

3.2.4. Agent Usage Experience

Participants’ agent knowledge was assessed by asking participants to rate how familiar they were with AI and AI virtual agents (e.g., chatbots and smart speakers) on a 7-point scale (1 = not familiar at all; 7 = very familiar) [25]; its score was the mean rating (ω = 0.88). Participants were also asked to indicate their usage of commercial AI virtual agents in the past month via a multiple-choice question; those with usage history in the past month further rated their usage frequency (1 = once a month; 7 = many times a day) and satisfaction (1 = not satisfied at all; 7 = very satisfied) on 7-point scales [64]. Moreover, all participants rated their general trust in these agents on a 7-point scale (1 = do not trust at all; 7 = very trust) [65].

3.2.5. Recognition of Ostracism

Participants’ recognition of ostracism was assessed by the mean of two items (e.g., “Did the other participant exclude Paxly during the game?”) on a 7-point scale (1 = definitely not; 7 = definitely yes; ω = 0.91), adapted from Paolini et al. [37]. To conceal the purpose of these two items as a manipulation check, we included two filler questions related to game play experience (e.g., “Did the game connect to the server quickly and run well?”) [66].

3.3. Participants

We recruited a total of 318 participants from Prolific Academic. Following Prolific’s reward policy, all participants received £2.25 for approximately 15 min of study participation. We removed 74 participants from the initial sample, as they (1) did not complete the experiment (n = 1), (2) did not receive the intended experimental manipulation (i.e., the HUMAN and AGENT players’ ball-tossing behaviour deviated from the expected pattern2; n = 44), or (3) had prior Cyberball research experience (n = 29). Exclusions resulted in a final sample of N = 244, which exceeds the minimum unadjusted sample size of 200, as indicated by a priori power analysis [67] with d = 0.40, α = 0.05, and 80% power for both one-way between-subjects and 2 × 2 mixed designs. Details can be found in the Supporting Information section, Participant Recruitment and Sample Size Estimation.

Of the 244 included participants, 130 were female and 114 were male (sex assigned at birth), aged 18 to 62 (M =28.02, SD =7.78). Most of them identified as White (68.44%), followed by Black (22.13%), Mixed (5.33%), Asian (2.05%), and Other (2.05%). Participants resided in 19 countries, mostly in Western Europe (53.28%), Africa (25.41%), and Central/Eastern Europe (13.11%); the remainder were in North America (7.38%), Oceania (0.41%), and Middle East (0.41%).

3.4. Data Analyses

3.4.1. Data Cleaning and Descriptive Analyses

Missing data and outlier treatment as well as descriptive analyses were carried out in SPSS v29.0. There was missing data for response time (0.61%), age (0.82%), and usage satisfaction (16.39%). The relatively high missing data rate for usage satisfaction was due to participants without agent usage in the past month (usage frequency =0) not being asked to report satisfaction; we thus used the expectation–maximisation algorithm for imputation. We used windsorisation to handle outliers (0.82%–1.64%) that exceeded the ±3 standard deviation (SD) threshold across all the data [68]. Descriptive analyses included calculating means and SDs (or frequencies) and checking variable distributions via histograms. One variable, anger towards coplayers, was removed from inferential analyses due to its distribution (see Results section for details).

3.4.2. Reliability Testing and Covariate Selection

The following analyses3 were run in R v4.2.2. We calculated ω coefficients based on confirmatory factor analysis as reliability estimates [73]. To remedy the uncertainty in a priori covariate selection, we employed the least absolute shrinkage and selection operator (LASSO) regression to identify the influential user-characteristic covariates [70]. The identified covariates were then adjusted for in the later primary and exploratory analyses.

3.4.3. Primary Analyses

We performed primary analyses to address RQ1 (How do participants behave when they observe an AI virtual agent being ostracised (versus treated fairly) by another human?) and RQ2 (How do participants perceive the ostracised agent and the human ostraciser, compared to corresponding perceptions in the fair play condition?).

For RQ1, we employed the general linear model (GLM) framework to examine the effects of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) on ball-tossing tendency. We then employed the linear mixed model (LMM) framework to examine the effects of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) and coplayer type (AGENT vs. HUMAN) on ball-tossing response time, following Singmann and Kellen [72]. That is, the fixed-effects-only model (i.e., traditional mixed ANOVA) was extended by adding by-participant random intercepts. It was to account for the correlations among data points obtained from one participant; for example, some participants generally had longer response times than the average, whereas others had shorter response times. For RQ2, we employed the GLM framework to examine the effects of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) on anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player and identification with the HUMAN player. We employed the LMM framework to examine the effects of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) and coplayer type (AGENT vs. HUMAN) on sympathy towards coplayers and impression of coplayers.

3.4.4. Exploratory Analyses

For RQ3 (Do user characteristics moderate the effects of Cyberball condition on individuals’ behaviour and perceptions?), we performed exploratory analyses. We explored the potential roles of user characteristics—agent usage experience, dispositional traits, and demographics—as moderators of the effects observed in the primary analyses. Specifically, we conducted a series of GLM analyses to examine how specific user characteristics might moderate the effect of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) on ball-tossing tendency, anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player, and identification with the HUMAN player, separately. We conducted LMM analyses to examine how specific user characteristics might moderate the effects of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) and coplayer type (AGENT vs. HUMAN) on ball-tossing response time, sympathy towards coplayers, and impression of coplayers, separately.

In addition, it should be mentioned that for all LMM analyses, we used the Satterthwaite’s approximation to calculate degrees of freedom (dfs) and p values. We calculated partial eta-squared () and semi-partial marginal R-squared (ΔR2; LMM only) as effect size estimates. With an interaction present, we employed the Johnson–Neyman technique and performed the simple effects analysis. Prior to the analyses, deviation coding was applied to categorical variables. Model assumptions and multicollinearity were checked. For all models, the homoscedasticity assumptions were met, and visual inspection of Q-Q plots showed reasonably normal distributions for the residuals and random effects (LMM only); the values of variance inflation factors were under 3.3. Thus, assumption violations and multicollinearity were not strong concerns in our data.

4. Results

Descriptive statistics for all variables, both within and collapsed across conditions, can be found in the Supporting Information section, Table S1. Among the variables, the data for “anger towards coplayers” displayed a highly skewed distribution, with 368 (75.41%) out of 488 observations (244 participants) reporting no anger at all. Common techniques for non-normality (e.g., transforming data, relying on the asymptotic normality assumption, and using non-parametric bootstrapping) are not suitable for highly skewed data [74]. Also, with the current sample size, the tail of the distribution could not be modelled accurately to draw robust inferences. Therefore, we removed this variable from inferential analyses.

To test the effectiveness of the Cyberball manipulation, we analysed the effect of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) on recognition of ostracism. Due to the presence of heteroscedasticity (p < 0.001), Welch’s ANOVA was performed. Results showed the expected significant effect of Cyberball condition, with participants in the exclusion condition (M = 4.05, SD = 1.74) reporting higher recognition of the agent’s ostracised state than participants in the fair play condition (M = 1.62, SD = 1.22), F(1, 210.14) = 157.60, p < 0.001, .

4.1. Primary Analyses

Before running primary analyses, we employed LASSO regressions to identify the influential user-characteristic covariates for six dependent variables: ball-tossing tendency, response time, sympathy towards coplayers, impression of coplayers, anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player, and identification with the HUMAN player. The rationale for using LASSO can be found in the Supporting Information section, LASSO regression, with the complete list of covariates identified presented in the Supporting Information section, Table S2. The following primary and exploratory analyses were adjusted for LASSO-identified covariates. The analyses were repeated without covariate adjustment and yielded consistent results (see the Supporting Information section, Analyses Without Covariates).

4.1.1. Ball-Tossing Tendency

This index is a ratio difference value, calculated by subtracting the ratio of ball tosses to the HUMAN player from that to the AGENT player. The GLM analysis showed a significant effect of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) on ball-tossing tendency, F(1, 242) = 16.49, p < 0.001, ; as illustrated in Figure 3, the average value for ball-tossing tendency in the exclusion condition (M = 4.43%, SD = 0.26) was higher than that in the fair play condition (M = −8.01%, SD = 0.22). Also, this value was positive in the exclusion condition, indicating a higher ratio of ball tosses to the AGENT player than to the HUMAN player, while this value was negative in the fair play condition, indicating a higher ratio of ball tosses to the HUMAN player than to the AGENT player.

4.1.2. Response Time

This index is the mean response time for the participant to make the decision and toss the ball to each coplayer. We conducted an LMM analysis with participants as the random effects grouping factor as well as Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play), coplayer type (AGENT vs. HUMAN), and their interaction as fixed effects terms. Results showed a significant main effect of Cyberball condition, F(1, 242.85) = 14.33, p < 0.001, , ΔR2 = 0.036; as illustrated in Figure 4, participants in the exclusion condition (M = 3.12, SD = 0.23) generally had longer response times (in seconds) than participants in the fair play condition (M = 3.01, SD = 0.22). The main effect of coplayer type was not significant, F(1, 242.09) = 1.39, p = 0.239. Additionally, the interaction between Cyberball condition and coplayer type was not significant, F(1, 242.09) = 2.84, p = 0.093.

4.1.3. Sympathy

We conducted an LMM analysis with participants as the random effects grouping factor as well as Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play), coplayer type (AGENT vs. HUMAN), their interaction, and LASSO-identified covariates (i.e., openness, trait empathy, and agent trust) as fixed effects terms. Results showed that the main effect of Cyberball condition was not significant, F(1, 239.00) = 2.10, p = 0.148. The main effect of coplayer type was significant, F(1, 242.00) = 16.62, p < 0.001, , ΔR2 = 0.011; participants’ sympathy towards the HUMAN player (M = 4.66, SD = 2.26) was generally higher than towards the AGENT player (M = 4.08, SD = 2.29). The main effects were qualified by a significant interaction between Cyberball condition and coplayer type, F(1, 242.00) = 7.49, p = 0.007, , ΔR2 = 0.005. The follow-up analysis of the simple effects of Cyberball condition was performed. As illustrated in Figure 5, participants in the exclusion condition reported higher sympathy towards the AGENT player than participants in the fair play condition, F(1, 331.67) = 5.97, p = 0.015, ; however, there was no statistical difference in sympathy towards the HUMAN player between participants in the two conditions, F(1, 331.67) = 0.04, p = 0.840.

4.1.4. Impression

We conducted an LMM analysis with participants as the random effects grouping factor as well as Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play), coplayer type (AGENT vs. HUMAN), their interaction, and LASSO-identified covariates (i.e., trait empathy, agent trust, and usage satisfaction) as fixed effects terms. Results showed that the main effect of Cyberball condition was not significant, F(1, 239.00) = 0.87, p = 0.352. The main effect of coplayer type was significant, F(1, 242.00) = 29.04, p < 0.001, , ΔR2 = 0.029; participants’ impression of the HUMAN player (M = 4.81, SD = 0.92) was generally more favourable than that of the AGENT player (M = 4.50, SD = 1.01). The interaction between Cyberball condition and coplayer type was not significant, F(1, 242.00) = 1.16, p = 0.282.

4.1.5. Anthropomorphism and Identification

We conducted a GLM analysis to examine the effect of Cyberball condition (exclusion vs. fair play) on anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player, adjusting for LASSO-identified covariates (i.e., neuroticism, trait empathy, agent trust, usage satisfaction, agent knowledge, and ethnicity). Results showed no statistical difference in anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player between participants in the two conditions, F(1, 236) = 0.23, p = 0.636. Likewise, for identification with the HUMAN player, the effect of Cyberball condition was not significant, F(1, 242) = 1.57, p = 0.212.

4.2. Exploratory Analyses

We explored the potential roles of user characteristics—agent usage experience, dispositional traits, and demographics—as moderators of the effects observed in the primary analyses. In terms of ball-tossing response time, impression, and identification, our data did not provide statistical evidence of a moderating effect of any of the user characteristics, while for ball-tossing tendency, sympathy, and anthropomorphism, we identified one moderator each. For simplicity, this section only presents the statistically significant results. All results, including nonsignificant ones, can be found in the Supporting Information section, Exploratory Analysis Results.

4.2.1. Ball-Tossing Tendency: Age as a Moderator

The GLM analysis showed a significant interaction effect of Cyberball condition and age on ball-tossing tendency, F(1, 238) = 9.55, p = 0.002, . The Johnson–Neyman technique (Figure 6(a)) showed significant mean differences in ball-tossing tendency between the two conditions when age was higher than 24; the strength of the effect of Cyberball condition was stronger with higher age. In addition, the analysis of the simple effects of age (Figure 6(b)) showed that the older the participants were, the lower their ball-tossing tendency (to the AGENT player) in the fair play condition, B = −0.006, SE = 0.003, 95% CI [−0.01, −0.0003], F(1, 238) = 4.30, p = 0.039, , while their ball-tossing tendency (to the AGENT player) in the exclusion condition was higher, B = 0.006, SE = 0.003, 95% CI [0.001, 0.01], F(1, 238) = 5.52, p = 0.020, . To explore possible reasons for age’s moderation on ball-tossing tendency, we further examined whether age moderated the effects of Cyberball condition on other dependent variables, recognition of ostracism, and task participation time, but neither main nor moderating effects of age were found.

4.2.2. Sympathy: Usage Frequency as a Moderator

The LMM analysis showed a marginally significant three-way interaction among Cyberball condition, coplayer type, and usage frequency, F(1, 240.00) = 3.88, p = 0.050, , ΔR2 = 0.003. The Johnson–Neyman technique (Figure 7(a)) showed the significant interaction effect of Cyberball condition and coplayer type on sympathy when the level of usage frequency was lower than 3.86. In addition, the analysis of the simple effects of usage frequency (Figure 7(b)) showed that in the fair play condition, higher usage frequency was significantly associated with lower sympathy towards both the AGENT, B = −0.19, SE = 0.09, 95% CI [−0.37, −0.01], F(1, 327.17) = 4.33, p = 0.038, , and HUMAN players, B = −0.32, SE = 0.09, 95% CI [−0.50, −0.14], F(1, 327.17) = 12.07, p < 0.001, . However, in the exclusion condition, usage frequency was not significantly associated with sympathy towards either the AGENT, B = 0.04, SE = 0.09, 95% CI [−0.13, 0.22], F(1, 329.14) = 0.25, p = 0.619, or HUMAN players, B = 0.12, SE = 0.09, 95% CI [−0.05, 0.30], F(1, 329.14) = 1.88, p = 0.172.

4.2.3. Anthropomorphism: Usage Satisfaction as a Moderator

The GLM analysis showed a significant interaction effect of Cyberball condition and usage satisfaction on anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player, F(1, 235) = 5.34, p = 0.022, . The Johnson–Neyman technique (Figure 8(a)) showed significant mean differences in anthropomorphism between the two conditions when the level of usage satisfaction was lower than 3.81. In addition, the analysis of the simple effects of usage satisfaction (Figure 8(b)) showed that higher usage satisfaction was significantly associated with higher anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player in the fair play condition, B = 0.40, SE = 0.15, 95% CI [0.11, 0.69], F(1, 235) = 7.46, p = 0.007, . However, this association was not significant in the exclusion condition, B = 0.02, SE = 0.12, 95% CI [−0.22, 0.26], F(1, 235) = 0.04, p = 0.841. These results are consistent with the available case analysis on the original data, which also showed a significant moderating effect on usage satisfaction (see the Supporting Information section, Examining the Moderation of Usage Satisfaction on the Unimputed Data).

5. Discussion

This study is aimed at investigating humans’ tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings. To this end, we conducted a 2 × 2 mixed-design online experiment employing the Cyberball paradigm to investigate how participants responded when they observed an AI virtual agent being ostracised or treated fairly by another human in Cyberball. We distinguished between mindless and mindful human responses by operationalising participants’ objective, real-time behaviour during Cyberball as mindless responses, and their subjective, retrospective perceptions as mindful responses. Furthermore, we explored whether individual differences would influence the tendency to treat AI virtual agents as social beings by examining the potential moderating effects of a range of user characteristics. In the following, we compare our results with those from human–human Cyberball research and then discuss the theoretical and design implications of this study, as well as its limitations and future research directions.

5.1. Participants Mindlessly Responded to Agents as They Would to Other Humans

RQ1: How do participants behave when they observe an AI virtual agent being ostracised (versus treated fairly) by another human? Compared to the fair play condition, the value for ball-tossing tendency (to the AGENT player) in the exclusion condition was significantly higher; also, there was a higher ratio of ball tosses to the ostracised AGENT player than to the HUMAN player. These results align with findings from human–human Cyberball research [34–36]. Therefore, participants applied the social norm of inclusion and compensated the ostracised agent by tossing the ball to them more frequently, as people would when observing human–human ostracism. Additionally, in the fair play condition, there was a higher ball-tossing ratio to the HUMAN player than to the AGENT player, contrasting with human–human Cyberball findings that people moderately expect fair distribution [36] and show no ball-tossing bias [35]; this discrepancy indicates a human bias, as previously reported [75, 76], with participants favouring interacting with another human fellow over an agent. However, the human bias did not counteract the socially normative behaviour of inclusion, as evidenced by a higher ball-tossing ratio to the ostracised AGENT player in the exclusion condition.

Moreover, the human bias in fair play indicates that participants’ compensation behaviour towards the ostracised agent went beyond equalising ball distribution. Neuroimaging evidence shows that observing human–human Cyberball ostracism and subsequent compensation activates brain regions linked to mentalisation and empathy for social pain [35, 53]. Observing ostracism also causes need threat and heightened negative mood [77], and further prosocial behaviour after Cyberball [37, 78]. Accordingly, compensation behaviour in Cyberball is prosocial, not just a means to balance the game or a preference to toss forward. Overall, our findings demonstrate that individuals tend to mindlessly treat AI virtual agents as social beings.

In terms of response time, compared to the fair play condition, participants in the exclusion condition generally had longer ball-tossing response times. In both Cyberball conditions, we found no statistical differences in ball-tossing response times between the HUMAN and AGENT players. As response time has been an under-studied behavioural index, we are unable to compare these results with human–human Cyberball findings. However, we would like to emphasise that the measure of response time here was not indicative of “decision time”. It was the mean response time for participants to make the decision and toss the ball to each coplayer across trials; as such, this time included the physical time it took for the ball to travel to the coplayer. More importantly, the study imposed a concurrent mental visualisation task during ball-tossing, further complicating the interpretation of this response time. Additionally, the response time was recorded in seconds rather than milliseconds, resulting in a lower level of precision than is typically expected in reaction time measurements. Given these constraints, we acknowledge that the response time data in our study may unfortunately not provide robust results, and caution is warranted when speculating on these results.

5.2. Participants Did Not Mindfully Perceive Agents as Comparable to Humans

RQ2: How do participants perceive the ostracised agent and the human ostraciser, compared to corresponding perceptions in the fair play condition? Participants in the exclusion condition reported higher sympathy towards the AGENT player than participants in the fair play condition, consistent with human–human research showing a significant effect of Cyberball condition on sympathy towards the target [39]. Participants’ sympathy towards the HUMAN player did not significantly differ between the two conditions, and it was generally higher than towards the AGENT player. These results diverge from human–human Cyberball research [36]. In our study, participants’ sympathy towards the HUMAN player remained consistent, regardless of whether the HUMAN player ostracised the AGENT player or not. That is, even though sympathy towards the ostracised agent increased, participants did not blame the human ostraciser for violating the inclusion norm; instead, they maintained their sympathy or emotional connection with the human ostraciser. This suggests a robust human bias (i.e., human favouritism) in their conscious perceptions, with individuals mindfully positioning AI virtual agents lower than humans. This speculation aligns with previous research showing that individuals often report more positive subjective perceptions of human interaction partners compared to agents (e.g., [55–57]).

Furthermore, we found no statistical difference in participants’ impression of the AGENT player between the fair play and exclusion conditions, mirroring human–human Cyberball findings that whether a person is ostracised or not does not impact others’ impression of them [37, 38]. There was no statistical difference in impression of and identification with the HUMAN player between the two conditions. These results, however, contradict human–human findings that ostracising behaviour lowers people’s impressions of the perpetrator [37, 38]. The contradiction can again be explained by a robust human bias that protected participants’ impression of the ostraciser when the target was a virtual agent. Additionally, there was no statistical difference in anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player between the two conditions. This result, although not directly comparable, is inconsistent with the human–human finding that the ostracised target is perceived with lower humanness [38]. When individuals observe another human being ostracised, they appear to justify the ostracism by denying the humanness of the ostracised target [38]. However, in our study, when the target is a virtual agent, participants may not need to rationalise the ostracism, implying that they did not view the agent’s experience as equivalent to that of a human.

Overall, the data pattern of retrospective perceptions revealed a complicated and nuanced picture of how the AGENT player was perceived. Participants reported higher sympathy towards the ostracised AGENT player, implying they attributed some human-like qualities to the agent. However, participants did not devalue or reduce emotional connection with the HUMAN player for ostracising, indicating they did not equate the agent’s experience with that of an ostracised human. The robust human bias in participants’ perceptions inhibited their mindful application of the inclusion norm. These results demonstrate that individuals do not mindfully perceive AI virtual agents as comparable to humans.

5.3. Moderating Effects of User Characteristics

RQ3: Do user characteristics moderate the effects of Cyberball condition on individuals’ behaviour and perceptions? For ball-tossing behaviour, age was the only user characteristic that showed a moderating effect; the strength of the effect of Cyberball condition on ball-tossing tendency was weaker with younger age, and this effect was not significant for age ≤ 23. This aligns with recent studies showing that older adults apply the politeness norm from human–human interaction to smart speakers and robots, but younger adults do not [79, 80]. In addition, it has been found that child, adolescent, and young adult samples all show compensation behaviour when observing human–human ostracism (e.g., [35, 51, 78]). We, thus, see two possible explanations for age’s moderation in our study. First, compared to older participants, younger participants could have different understandings of Cyberball contexts or varying levels of seriousness in participation. Yet, this seems less likely because analyses of age’s influence on the effects of Cyberball condition on manipulation check and study participation time did not reveal a moderating or main effect of age.

The second, more intriguing explanation relates to the human brain’s co-development with technology [81]. Younger generations, growing up with increasingly interactive technologies, may have adapted to these technologies during early brain development. Hence, they may have developed specific scripts for interacting with AI virtual agents and with other humans involved, rather than using social scripts from human–human interaction. This could explain why younger participants were less likely to mindlessly apply the inclusion norm, with age ≤ 23 showing no such application. Notably, while the mature brain continues to have plasticity, allowing for learning, adaptation and recovery, brain plasticity is most pronounced and responsive during childhood [82, 83]. Thus, while other age groups may also engage with these technologies frequently, their childhood experiences and early brain development followed a traditional way of interacting; for them, simply more agent usage experience may not be enough to prevent the mindless application of the inclusion norm. This explanation fits with our data pattern that only age (no other user characteristics) showed a moderating effect, but further investigations are warranted.

The observed trend that the older the participants were, the higher the ball-tossing tendency to the ostracised AGENT player may also relate to age-related shifts in moral judgement. Ostracism can be interpreted as a moral violation. As individuals age, they tend to prioritise moral values and avoid harm to others [84, 85]. Such heightened sensitivity to moral violations could lead older participants to show more compensation towards the ostracised AGENT player, compared to younger participants.

We further explored the moderating effects of user characteristics on participants’ perceptions, motivated by seeking whether certain groups of participants mindfully perceived agents as comparable to humans. Our data did not provide evidence to support this but revealed two other interesting findings. First, usage frequency moderated the effects of Cyberball condition and coplayer type on sympathy. A higher frequency of AI virtual agent use in the past month was associated with lower baseline sympathy towards both coplayers in the fair play condition, while the associations were not significant in the exclusion condition. Frequent agent users seem to show reduced sympathy or emotional connection with others, though this association may vary or disappear when other factors come into play (e.g., ostracism in this study). This implies the complicated relationships between human–agent and human–human interactions. A recent survey study also found that human–chatbot interaction could threaten or facilitate human–human interaction in different contexts [86]. But we would like to stress that inferring causality based on the current study design is premature, and it is, thus, uncertain whether frequent agent use would reduce sympathy or vice versa.

Second, usage satisfaction moderated the effect of Cyberball’s condition on anthropomorphism. In the fair play condition, participants who were more satisfied with the agent(s) they used in daily lives perceived higher anthropomorphism towards the AGENT player, consistent with other studies linking user satisfaction and anthropomorphism in AI virtual agents [87, 88]. This indicates that the positive usage experience may carry over to shape individuals’ initial perceptions of similar virtual agents. We speculate this carryover effect reflects a human cognitive bias similar to an “extended halo effect” [89], where the “halo” of positive experience with one agent extends to colour perceptions of similar agents. However, this effect could be influenced by the attitudes and behaviour of others (e.g., the HUMAN player in this study) towards that agent, as shown in the exclusion condition where participants’ usage satisfaction was not associated with anthropomorphism.

5.4. Theoretical and Design Implications

Our findings demonstrate that individuals tend to mindlessly treat AI virtual agents as social beings, supporting the basic ideas of the media equation theory [6]. The application of this theory has been fuelled by AI advances that bring increasingly interactive artefacts into existence, with recent systematic reviews revealing its popularity in human–agent interaction research [90, 91]. We further found that age (no other user characteristics) influenced the tendency to mindlessly treat agents as social beings, with this tendency diminishing with younger age. Alongside research investigating the politeness norm in human–agent interaction [79, 80], we suggest that the media equation theory may be losing its generalisability, necessitating the development of relevant theories focused on young age groups.

Furthermore, building upon prior studies showing how specific perceptions of robots can vary depending on whether Type 1 or Type 2 processing is involved [20–22], we applied the dual-processing model to examine both mindless and mindful human responses during human–agent interaction. This extended the media equation theory, which traditionally focused on mindless human responses [6, 92]. In addition, we used the Cyberball paradigm and followed Lombard and Xu’s [23] suggestions to facilitate differentiation, operationalising participants’ objective, real-time behaviour during Cyberball as mindless responses, and their subjective, retrospective perceptions as mindful responses; this approach allowed us to identify the differences between participants’ mindless and mindful responses. Our study contributes to the scholarly call to address the stalemated theoretical development of the human side of human–computer/agent interaction [93].

This study also has implications for the design of AI virtual agents. First, our finding that participants mindlessly applied the social norm of inclusion to AI virtual agents aligns with the recent design guideline for human–AI interaction instructing them to “match relevant social norms” [94]. Agent design needs to take into account socio-psychological mechanisms (e.g., norms, rules, and schemas) that underlie daily interactions. For instance, the social norm of inclusion may be considered in the context of human–agent collaboration. With these agents becoming popular in collaborative tasks, continuous engagement would increase users’ familiarity and trigger their Type 1 processing, leading to frequent mindless interactions; users, thus, would mindlessly include the agent as a real team member and engage with it socially, which suggests designing agents attuned to the inclusion norm.

Noteworthily, this design consideration does not mean that AI virtual agents should be designed human-like. Especially if the agents’ capabilities do not match their human-like appearance, users may engage in Type 2 processing more frequently, generating mindful responses; they, thus, may feel heightened eeriness [95] and experience lower learnability and effectiveness when performing tasks with the agents [96]. From another perspective, because individuals mindlessly apply social norms from human–human interaction to agents, might they, in turn, inadvertently transfer the way they treat agents to other humans? Might the agents’ human-likeness be a catalyst for such transfer? While beyond the scope of this study, we pose these questions to emphasise the need for caution in pursuing human-likeness.

Another consideration in agent design revolves around age or generational differences. Our finding on age’s moderation suggests that agent design would be more effective if tailored to specific age groups and supported by targeted user studies. For all-encompassing agents that aim to appeal to a wide generational audience, developers should consider generational and developmental differences in interactions.

5.5. Limitations and Future Research

This study has several limitations. First, we prioritised the examination of mindless responses during Cyberball interaction, with mindful responses examined post-interaction. While we would argue for the necessity of understanding mindless human responses (given that people often rely on Type 1 as a quick route of information processing, without engaging Type 2 for slower, analytical considerations; [97]), this limits the generalisation of our findings to interactions when Type 2 plays a more central role. Our examination of retrospective perceptions cannot be used to infer individuals’ responses during mindful interaction with agents. Second, we did not check ex post whether participants truly engaged in Type 1 processing, generating mindless ball-tossing behaviour, and Type 2 processing after Cyberball, generating mindful perceptions, while some participants could have failed to do so.

Third, Cyberball is a ball-tossing, kinesic game, whereas the common interaction mode for AI virtual agents is via written or spoken natural language in real-life scenarios [97]; this divergence could have conflicted with some participants’ expectations and affected their responses. Moreover, we used a commonly-used Cyberball application [58], which is well designed to achieve experimental manipulation without adding unknown confounds, yet it compromises the task fidelity; the mere use of the cover study, profile images, and player names was possibly insufficient to distinguish the identities of two coplayers clearly. Fourth, our recruitment was limited to most OECD countries and South Africa, as per Prolific’s coverage [99]. Also, demographic data were directly exported from Prolific, which provided “sex” but not “gender” data—a detail that could yield different outcomes. Another important limitation concerns the online study administration. While our study benefitted from its advantages in reaching a larger and more diverse sample and providing an anonymous environment [100], these came at the cost of the reduced rigorous control over experimental conditions. Despite the use of participant selection criteria and attention checks, the remote nature of the online experiment inherently limits our ability to closely monitor participant engagement and the environment in which they participated.

To build upon the current findings, a follow-up could probe mindful responses to agents during ongoing real-time interaction and explore the transition and interplay between mindful and mindless responses. When investigating mindless responses, the research could also impose short time limits to suppress Type 2 processing, apart from concurrent working memory loads [101]. Future research could also include participants’ thinking dispositions in analyses, as these dispositions can influence how a response initially primed by Type 1/2 processing is ultimately generated [17]. In addition, to confirm whether our finding on age’s moderation is due to the human brain’s co-development with technology, future research could consider using neuroscience approaches to evaluate neural activities during human–agent interaction. The lack of compensation behaviour towards the ostracised agent for participants aged ≤ 23, as well as their lack of human bias during fair play ball-tossing, suggests that longitudinal research designs targeting young age groups could be valuable [102]. Apart from age, two other exploratory findings—the association between agent usage frequency and sympathy, and the carryover effect of positive usage experience—also need further investigations to confirm that they are not the results of unique features of the current study. Finally, while this study focused on human–agent interaction in the observing ostracism situation, future work could explore other interaction scenarios and social norms and examine these in different contexts, including laboratory and field studies, to broaden the generalisability of our findings.

Endnotes

1The media equation theory originated in the book The Media Equation: How People Treat Computers, Television, and New Media Like Real People and Places, wherein Byron Reeves and Clifford Nass proposed that “media equal real life” based on a series of experimental studies [6]. The theory contains two themes: (1) audience responses to media as if they were real physical spaces, and (2) user responses to computers and media agents as if they were real social beings. This study concerns the second theme that has been applied in many human-agent interaction studies.

2This criterion relates to a programming constraint in the Cyberball application. It allows for programming the coplayers’ ball-tossing behaviour within a fixed maximum total number of ball tosses. Due to this fixation and the uncertainty of the participants’ behaviour, the AGENT and HUMAN players cannot be pre-programmed to always meet the experimental conditions (i.e., exclusion and fair play), leading to occasional deviations from the expected patterns. We addressed this by testing multiple behavioural programming approaches and conducted corresponding simulations (10, 000 runs); we then selected the approach that yielded the best simulation result. The a-priori sample size was estimated based on this. Details can be found in the Supporting Information section.

3Please note that data analyses have deviations from preregistration. After reviewing recent statistical literature (e.g., [69, 70]), we decided to use LASSO regressions to identify influential user-characteristic covariates. As explained in the User Characteristics section, while our primary interest in user characteristics is in their moderating effects, it is also necessary to consider them as potential covariates to control for confounding. Moreover, following (e.g., [71, 72]), we extended the traditional mixed ANOVA by adding by-participant random intercepts (i.e., using the LMM framework), which was to account for correlations among data points obtained from one participant.
